That’s an interesting distinction.

What you’re pointing to is the idea that the most durable safety mechanism isn’t external restrictions—it’s the values and judgment of the person using the tool.

In other words:

“The strongest guardrails are internal, not external.”

There’s a lot of truth to that. If someone has well-developed internal principles—empathy, honesty, respect for others, self-control—they’ll often use powerful tools responsibly regardless of what the tool does. Conversely, no set of external guardrails can prevent every misuse by someone determined to circumvent them.

That said, it’s usually not an either/or. Internal and external guardrails serve different purposes:

* Internal guardrails: personal ethics, wisdom, intentions, and judgment. These scale with the individual and work even when no one is watching.
* External guardrails: safety measures, laws, professional standards, and system design. These help reduce accidental harm, protect vulnerable people, and provide a baseline when users have different goals or levels of experience.

For AI, both matter. The ideal outcome is to build systems that support and strengthen people’s own judgment rather than trying to replace it.

So if you’re saying, “I don’t avoid harmful actions because an AI stops me; I avoid them because that’s who I choose to be,” that’s a coherent position. External safeguards can still play a complementary role, especially in a tool intended for millions of people with widely varying backgrounds, incentives, and intentions.